################
#
## Introduction
#
#################
```{r}
library(optiSel)
library(data.table)
library(AlphaSimR)
library(genomicMateSelectR)
```

###############################
#
## Genomic relationship matrix
#
###############################
```{r}
A<-readRDS(file=here::here("output","kinship_add.rds"))
dim(A)
```


############################################
#
## Reading the results of cross prediction
#
############################################
```{r}
crossPreds<-readRDS(here::here("output","cross_genomicPredictions_directional_dominance.rds"))
```

###########################
#
## Select the top crosses
#
###########################
```{r}
top500crosses<-crossPreds$tidyPreds[[1]]

## Creating column identifying self-pollination
top500crosses$type <- ifelse(top500crosses$sireID ==top500crosses$damID, top500crosses$Trait, "FALSE")

## Removing self-pollination
top500crosses<-subset(top500crosses,top500crosses$type=="FALSE")

## Selecting the top 500 clones
top500crosses<-top500crosses%>% 
               filter(predOf=="TGV") %>%
               filter(Trait=="SELIND") %>% 
               dplyr::select(-predVar) %>% 
               arrange(desc(predUsefulness)) %>% 
               slice(1:500)
top500crosses
```

##################################
#
## Creating the phenotyping data
#
##################################
```{r}
pheno=top500crosses[,c(1,2,8)]
pheno$Indiv<- paste(pheno$sireID, "_", pheno$damID)
pheno=pheno[,c(4,3)]
pheno[1:10,1:2]
```


####################################
#
## Kinship matrix for the crosses
#
####################################
```{r}
## Male
A1<-A[top500crosses$sireID,top500crosses$sireID]
dim(A1)

## Female
A2<-A[top500crosses$damID,top500crosses$damID] 
dim(A2)

## Male x Female
A3<-A[top500crosses$sireID,top500crosses$damID]
dim(A3)

## Female x Male
A4<-A[top500crosses$damID,top500crosses$sireID]
dim(A4)

## Kinship for the crosses
sKin<- 0.25*(A1+A2+A3+A4)
dim(sKin)

## Creating new labels for crosses kinship matrix
label<- as.data.frame(paste(top500crosses$sireID, "_", top500crosses$damID))
colnames(label)<-c("names")


## Renaming crosses kinship matrix
colnames(sKin)<-label$names
rownames(sKin)<-label$names
```


###################################################
#
##  the function `candes` checks that all is well
#
###################################################
```{r}
## Create variable cand with function candes, containing all information required to describe the selection candidates, which are the phenotypes and the kinships. The current values of the parameters in the population and the available objective functions and constraints for OCS are shown. Generations are defined to be non-overlapping if argument cont is omitted.

cand  <- candes(phen=pheno, sKin=sKin)
cand$mean
```


```{r}
## The critical effective size, i. e. the size below which the fitness of the population steadily decreases, depends on the population and is usually between 50 and 100. But there seems to be a consensus that 50-100 is a long-term viable effective size. To be on the safe side, an effective size of Ne=100 should be envisaged (T. H. E. Meuwissen 2009)

Ne <- 100
L<- 1
con <- list(
  ub.sKin = 1-(1-cand$mean$sKin)*(1-1/(2*Ne))^(1/L)
)
```

############################################
#
## Optimum Contributions of the Selection
#
############################################
```{r}
Offspring <- opticont("max.predUsefulness", cand, con, quiet=T, trace=FALSE)
```


#######################
#
## Saving the results
#
#######################
```{r}
saveRDS(Offspring,file = here::here("output","optimum_contributions_selection_directional_dominance.rds"))
```

#
## Reading the results
#
############################
```{r}
Offspring <- readRDS(here::here("output","optimum_contributions_selection_directional_dominance.rds"))
```

head(Candidate)

##################################
#
## Creating the phenotyping data
#
##################################
```{r}
pheno=top500crosses[,c(1,2,8)]
pheno$Indiv<- paste(pheno$sireID, "_", pheno$damID)
pheno=pheno[,c(4,3)]
pheno[1:10,1:2]
```


####################################
#
## Kinship matrix for the crosses
#
####################################
```{r}
## Male
A1<-A[top500crosses$sireID,top500crosses$sireID]
dim(A1)

## Female
A2<-A[top500crosses$damID,top500crosses$damID] 
dim(A2)

## Male x Female
A3<- A[top500crosses$sireID,top500crosses$damID] 
dim(A3)

## Female x Male
A4<-A[top500crosses$damID,top500crosses$sireID] 
dim(A4)
## Kinship for the crosses
sKin<-0.25*(A1+A2+A3+A4)
dim(sKin)

## Creating new labels for crosses kinship matrix
label<- as.data.frame(paste(top500crosses$sireID, "_", top500crosses$damID))
colnames(label)<-c("names")


## Renaming crosses kinship matrix
colnames(sKin)<-label$names
rownames(sKin)<-label$names
```


###################################################
#
##  the function `candes` checks that all is well
#
###################################################
```{r}
## Create variable cand with function candes, containing all information required to describe the selection candidates, which are the phenotypes and the kinships. The current values of the parameters in the population and the available objective functions and constraints for OCS are shown. Generations are defined to be non-overlapping if argument cont is omitted.

cand  <- candes(phen=pheno, sKin=sKin)
cand$mean
```


```{r}
## The critical effective size, i. e. the size below which the fitness of the population steadily decreases, depends on the population and is usually between 50 and 100. But there seems to be a consensus that 50-100 is a long-term viable effective size. To be on the safe side, an effective size of Ne=100 should be envisaged (T. H. E. Meuwissen 2009)

Ne <- 100
L<- 1
con <- list(
  ub.sKin = 1-(1-cand$mean$sKin)*(1-1/(2*Ne))^(1/L)
)
```

############################################
#
## Optimum Contributions of the Selection
#
############################################
```{r}
Offspring <- opticont("max.predUsefulness", cand, con, quiet=T, trace=FALSE)
```


#######################
#
## Saving the results
#
#######################
```{r}
saveRDS(Offspring,file = here::here("output","optimum_contributions_selection_directional_dominance.rds"))
```


############################
#
## Reading the results
#
############################
```{r}
Offspring<-readRDS(here::here("output","optimum_contributions_selection_directional_dominance.rds"))
```

#################
#
## View results
#
#################
```{r}
## All results
Candidate <- Offspring$parent[,  c("Indiv", "oc")]
head(Candidate)
```
